SIMPLE: tip
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tip
<hw>Tip</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Akin to D. & Dan.
<ets>tip</ets>, LG. & Sw. <ets>tipp</ets>, G. <ets>zipfel</ets>, and
probably to E. <ets>tap</ets> a plug, a pipe.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The point or extremity of anything; a pointed or somewhat sharply
rounded end; the end; <as>as, the <ex>tip</ex> of the finger; the
<ex>tip</ex> of a spear</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To the very <qex>tip</qex> of the nose.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An end piece or part; a piece, as a cap, nozzle,
ferrule, or point, applied to the extreme end of anything; <as>as, a
<ex>tip</ex> for an umbrella, a shoe, a gas burner, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Hat Manuf.)</fld> <def>A piece of stiffened lining
pasted on the inside of a hat crown.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A thin, boarded brush made of camel's hair, used by
gilders in lifting gold leaf.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Rubbish thrown from a quarry.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tip</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Tip
<hw>Tip</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Tipped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Tipping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To form a point upon; to cover
the tip, top, or end of; <as>as, to <ex>tip</ex> anything with gold or
silver</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With truncheon <qex>tipped</qex> with iron head.</q>
<rj><qau>Hudibras.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Tipped</qex> with jet,⟦br⟧
Fair ermines spotless as the snows they press.</q>
<rj><qau>Thomson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tip</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Tip
<hw>Tip</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Cf. LG. <ets>tippen</ets> to tap,
Sw. <ets>tippa</ets>, and E. <ets>tap</ets> to strike gently.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To strike slightly; to tap.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A third rogue <qex>tips</qex> me by the elbow.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To bestow a gift, or douceur, upon; to give a
present to; <as>as, to <ex>tip</ex> a servant</as>.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark> <rj><au>Thackeray.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To lower one end of, or to throw upon the end; to
tilt; <as>as, to <ex>tip</ex> a cask; to <ex>tip</ex> a
cart</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To tip off</b></col>, <cd>to pour out, as liquor.</cd> --
<col><b>To tip over</b></col>, <cd>to overturn.</cd> -- <col><b>To tip
the wink</b></col>, <cd>to direct a wink; to give a hint or suggestion
by, or as by, a wink.</cd> <mark>[Slang]</mark> <au>Pope.</au> --
<col><b>To tip up</b></col>, <cd>to turn partly over by raising one
end.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tip</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Tip
<hw>Tip</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To fall on, or incline to, one
side.</def> <rj><au>Bunyan.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To tip off</b></col>, <cd>to fall off by
tipping.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tip</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Tip
<hw>Tip</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Tip</er> to strike slightly,
and cf. <er>Tap</er> a slight blow.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A light
touch or blow; a tap.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A gift; a douceur; a fee.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A hint, or secret intimation, as to the chances in a
horse race, or the like.</def> <mark>[Sporting Cant]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tipcart</ent>⟦br⟧
